# ⚡ Conditional Annotations

Spring Boot uses conditional annotations to decide whether to create a bean.

---

## @ConditionalOnClass

Creates a bean only if a class exists.

```java id="jlwm118"
@ConditionalOnClass(DataSource.class)
```

---

## @ConditionalOnMissingBean

Creates a bean only if one does not already exist.

```java id="jlwm119"
@ConditionalOnMissingBean
```

---

## @ConditionalOnProperty

Creates a bean based on application properties.

```java id="jlwm120"
@ConditionalOnProperty(
    name="server.port"
)
```

---

## @ConditionalOnBean

Creates a bean only if another bean exists.

```java id="jlwm121"
@ConditionalOnBean
```

---

# 💻 Example of Auto Configured Bean

```java id="jlwm122"
@Bean
@ConditionalOnMissingBean
public ObjectMapper objectMapper() {

    return new ObjectMapper();

}
```

If no ObjectMapper exists, Spring Boot creates one automatically.

---

# 🚫 Excluding Auto Configuration

Sometimes you may not want a particular auto configuration.

Example:

```java id="jlwm123"
@SpringBootApplication(
exclude = {
DataSourceAutoConfiguration.class
})
public class DemoApplication {

}
```

---

# ⚙ application.properties

Auto Configuration can be customized.

Example:

```properties id="jlwm124"
server.port=9090

spring.datasource.url=
jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/studentdb
```

Spring Boot reads these properties and configures the application automatically.

